Just a small problem in your route. Modify it like this,

    {
        path: &#39;planlist/:departure/:destination/:date&#39;,
        component: ReservationComponent
    }

If you are routing from TS,

    this.router.navigate([&#39;planlist&#39;, departure, destination, date]);

Or from HTML,

    routerLink=&quot;/planlist/{{departure}}/{{destination}}/{{date}}&quot;

Yes, you can. The first thing you need to correct is the way to capture the variables using the path:
You&#39;ve got:

    path: &#39;planlist/:departure_:destination/:date&#39;,

The correct way is:

    path: &#39;planlist/:departure/:destination/:date&#39;,

The second thing you should do is call the method as follows:

    router.navigate([&#39;planlist&#39;, departure, destination, date]);

And to capture the value of the variables:

    const departure= this.route.snapshot.params[&#39;departure&#39;];
    const destination= this.route.snapshot.params[&#39;destination&#39;];
    const date= this.route.snapshot.params[&#39;date&#39;];

Yes, you can. You can do it using the queryParams feature.

For that, you need to correct the path to:

    path: &#39;planlist&#39;,

You send all the variables in the queryParams object as follows:

    router.navigate([&#39;planlist&#39;], { queryParams: { departure, destination, date } });

And the catch them like this:

     this.route
         .queryParamMap
             .pipe(
                 map(params =&gt; params.getAll()  || [])
             ).subscribe((params) =&gt; {
                 if (!!params.length) {
                     this.planlistVars= params;
                 }
             }).unsubscribe();

The key is **queryParamMap**, you can search more on Google or the official website of angular.
https://angular.io/api/router/ParamMap

